The '''University of Vermont College of Medicine''' is an [[Medical school in the United States|American medical school]] located in [[Burlington, Vermont]] and associated with the [[University of Vermont]] (UVM). Established in 1822, it is the nation's seventh oldest [[medical school]]. The primary [[teaching hospital]] for the UVM College of Medicine is [[Fletcher Allen Health Care]] in Burlington.

The UVM College of Medicine offers both [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] and [[MD/PhD]] programs. In 2007, there were 431 medical and 23 MD/PhD students enrolled.<ref name="2007-facts"/> Each class contains approximately 110 students; the entering class of 2015 contains 112 students.<ref name="uvm-com-article">{{cite web |url=http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmpr/?Page=News&storyID=12545 |title=University Communications : University of Vermont |format= |work= |accessdate=2008-10-09}}</ref>

The school's medical curriculum is known as the "Vermont Integrated Curriculum". It has both traditional, subject-based and more contemporary, organ/system-based components. The first 18 months of the curriculum are devoted to [[Medicine#Basic sciences|basic]] and [[clinical science]]; the remainder of the four-year program largely consists of [[clinical clerkship]]s.

The institution is one of the ten most-selective medical schools in the United States, with an acceptance rate of 4.0% annually. <ref>http://www.usnews.com/education/best-graduate-schools/articles/2011/04/05/10-medical-schools-with-lowest-acceptance-rates</ref>

==Education==
The UVM College of Medicine offers both [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] and [[MD/PhD]] programs. It enrolls approximately 100 students into the MD program, and four students into the MD/PhD program annually.

According to the institution, the UVM College of Medicine offers an "integrated" medical curriculum. This curriculum, known as the "Vermont Integrated Curriculum", or "VIC", is separated into three levels.<ref name="vic">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.uvm.edu/ome/TB1+RL+I.asp?SiteAreaID=515 |title=Vermont Integrated Curriculum |format= |work=UVM College of Medicine |accessdate=2008-09-28}}</ref> ''Level one/foundations'' is focused on [[Medicine#Basic sciences|basic]] and [[clinical science]]s and lasts 18 months. ''Level two/clinical clerkships'' is a 12-month period spent [[clinical rotation|rotating]] through various [[clinical clerkship]]s at [[Fletcher Allen Health Care]] and [[Maine Medical Center]]. In ''level three/advanced integration'', students continue rotating through clinical clerkships and [[acting internship]]s with additional responsibilities.

==Rank==
The UVM College of Medicine is highly ranked among American medical schools. For 2010, The University of Vermont College of Medicine was ranked by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' as 4th on the "Top Medical Schools&nbsp;— Primary Care" list and 8th on the "Top Medical Schools&nbsp;— Rural Medicine" list.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/grad/mdr/search/order+c_mdp_final_overall_rank | title = Top Medical Schools&nbsp;— Primary Care | work = America's Best Graduate Schools 2010 | publisher = [[U.S. News & World Report]] | accessdate = 2009-04-08 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>http://www.uvm.edu/~uvmpr/?Page=News&storyID=16482</ref>

==Affiliations==
The UVM College of Medicine is affiliated with four [[teaching hospital]]s, with the primary affiliate being [[Fletcher Allen Health Care]] in [[Burlington, Vermont]]. A long-standing affiliation with [[Maine Medical Center]] in [[Portland, Maine]] began in the late 1970s<ref name="theview-maine-ingredient">{{cite web |url=http://www.med.uvm.edu/admissions/downloads/Maine.pdf |title=The Maine Ingredient |format=PDF |work=The View |author=Edward Neuert |accessdate=2008-10-16}}</ref> but ended in February 2011.<ref name="mmc-pr">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmc.org/mmc_body.cfm?id=4666 |title=Maine Medical Center and Tufts create medical school program |format= |work= |accessdate=2008-10-16}}</ref> Three new hospitals took the place of MMC: Danbury Hospital in Danbury, Connecticut, Eastern Maine Medical Center in Bangor, Maine, and St. Mary's Hospital in West Palm Beach, Florida.<ref name="South Florida Hospital News">{{cite web |url=http://www.southfloridahospitalnews.com/education/default.asp?page=2 | title=St. Mary’s Medical Center Launches University of Vermont College of Medicine Medical Student Education Program |format= |work= |accessdate=2010-02-03}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

